{
  "id": "019d4187-71c6-7961-8fd4-7f79977d7f0f",
  "content": "# Agentic Retrieval Protocol -- Design Decisions (2026-03-31)\n\n## What: Server-side intelligence for agent-corvia interactions\nPush complex retrieval logic server-side (deterministic, portable). Keep agent instructions minimal (~20 lines). Five design areas across two tracks.\n\n## Key Decisions:\n1. Quality signals (confidence/suggestion/gap_detected) computed server-side in corvia_search response. Thresholds: high >= 0.65+3 results, medium >= 0.45, low = else.\n2. Suggestion generation is template-based, not LLM-generated (zero latency cost).\n3. corvia_context gets max_tokens param (hard cap 4000) + compact format for subagent prompts.\n4. Gap detection is implicit from search logs (ring buffer), surfaced in dashboard. NOT knowledge entries.\n5. Write deduplication at cosine > 0.90 blocks write; 0.80-0.90 warns; force_write bypasses.\n6. No explicit rating protocol for feedback. Implicit signals only (re-search patterns, write correlation).\n\n## Alternatives rejected:\n- LLM-based quality assessment (unreliable at ~70%)\n- Explicit gap reporting by agents (<20% compliance)\n- Time-based write triggers (no reliable timer in agent frameworks)\n- Write reminders (MCP is request-response, server cannot push)",
